In case of Iron deficiency anaemia, Oral Iron therapy should not be stopped even after the patient achieves a haemoglobin of &gt;12 mg/dL. After the haemoglobin target has been reached, iron supplementation should be continued for another 6 months in order to rebuild the depleted reserves.<br />
&nbsp;
<p><em><strong>Reference</strong>: Harrison&#39;s Principles of Internal Medicine, 21st edition, Page no 748-452.</em></p>

Acquired causes of pure red cell aplasia are all except NSAIDs. PRCA happens in cases of major ABO-mismatch between donor and recipient and is thought to be due to inhibition of donor erythroid progenitors by residual host isohemagglutinins Pure red cell hypoplasia with deletion of the long arm of a chromosome 5(5g-) is seen where the bone marrow represents lowered erythroid cells with normal granulocytic and megakaryocytic precursors. LEukemia and Lymphoma can present with PRCA. Most common Cause of PRCA is Parvovirus Drugs like:Phenytoin, azathioprine, Chloramphenicol,Procainamide and isoniazid can cause pure red cell aplasia.<br />
&nbsp;
<p><em><strong>Reference</strong>: Harrison&#39;s Principles of Internal Medicine, 21st edition, Page no 1496 .</em></p>

Iron Deficiency Anemia is a condition in which there is a decrease in the amount of healthy red blood cells, leading to anemia. Lab findings include decreased MCV and MCH, an elevated red cell distribution width, increased TIBC, and decrease in serum iron and ferritin levels.<br />
&nbsp;
<p><em><strong>Reference</strong>: Harrison&#39;s Principles of Internal Medicine, 21st edition, Page no 747-754 .</em></p>

The patient has all the features suggestive of Multiple Myeloma - renal failure / Bone discomfort likely due to lytic lesions and the presence of M Spikes. However, the patient also has &gt;20% Plasma cells in peripheral blood whereas in Multiple Myeloma - the monoclonal plasma cells are present in BM(Bone Marrow) and do not appear in the blood. When present in blood and more than 20% - it&#39;s classified as Plasma cell leukemia.<br />
&nbsp;
<p><em><strong>Reference</strong>: Harrison&#39;s Principles of Internal Medicine, 21st edition, Page no 866- 876</em>.</p>

CLL is typically diagnosed in the older population and is not curable with current treatment approaches. There is no advantage to early intervention and allogeneic bone marrow transplants are too toxic for this population. Instead, multiple drug therapy is preferred, such as Fludarabine and Chlorambucil, meaning diagnosis is not necessarily a prompt to initiate treatment.<br />
&nbsp;
<p><em><strong>Reference</strong>: Harrison&#39;s Principles of Internal Medicine, 21st edition, Page no 834-840</em>.</p>
